{"title_page": "Twenty Twelve", "text_new": "{{other uses|2012 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Twenty Twelve\n| image = Twenty Twelve.jpg\n| composer =\n| genre = [[Mockumentary]]\n| writer = [[John Morton (writer)|John Morton]]\n| director = John Morton\n| creator = John Morton\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| starring = [[Hugh Bonneville]]<br />[[Jessica Hynes]]<br />[[Amelia Bullmore]]<br />[[Olivia Colman]]<br />[[Vincent Franklin]]<br />[[Karl Theobald]]<br />[[Morven Christie]]\n| narrated = [[David Tennant]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Irving Berlin]]\n| opentheme = \"[[Let's Face the Music and Dance]]\" sung by [[Nat King Cole]]\n| company = [[BBC]]\n| editor =\n| executive_producer = [[Jon Plowman]]\n| producer = Paul Schlesinger\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| picture_format = ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]) [[576i]]<br />([[High-definition television|HDTV]]) [[1080i]]\n| audio_format = Stereo\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2011|3|14|df=y}}\n| last_aired =  {{End date|2012|7|24|df=y}}\n| num_series = 2\n| num_episodes = 13\n| list_episodes =\n| network = [[BBC Four]] (2011\u20132012)<br />[[BBC Two]] (2012)<br />[[BBC HD]]\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          =''[[W1A (TV series)|W1A]]''\n| website = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01f87nh\n}}\n'''''Twenty Twelve''''' is a [[BBC]] television comedy series written and directed by [[John Morton (writer)|John Morton]]. Starring [[Hugh Bonneville]], [[Jessica Hynes]] and [[Amelia Bullmore]], the programme is a spoof on-location [[mockumentary]] following the organisation of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]]. It was first broadcast on UK television station [[BBC Four]] in March 2011 to coincide with the 500-day countdown to the opening ceremony.\n\n''Twenty Twelve'' gained mainly positive reviews from critics, and a four-part second series was announced on 15 April 2011,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2011/04_april/15/twentytwelve.shtml | title=BBC Four recommissions hit comedy series Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC Press Office | date=15 April 2011 }}</ref> which began airing on 30 March 2012 on BBC Two.<ref>{{cite news | title=The British Comedy award-winning Twenty Twelve returns tonight for a four-part second series. | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2012/13/twenty-twelve.html | date= | accessdate=17 March 2012 | publisher=BBC Press Office }}</ref> A further three episodes of series 2 began airing from 10 July 2012.<ref>{{cite news | last=Mickel | first=Andrew | title='Twenty Twelve' gets third series | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a356455/twenty-twelve-gets-third-series.html | newspaper=Digital Spy | date=17 December 2011 }}</ref> The series' last episode was broadcast on 24 July 2012, three days before the opening ceremony of the London Olympic Games. \n\nSeveral core characters went on to appear in a sequel, [[W1A_(TV_series)|W1A]], in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/dec/05/bbc-twenty-twelve-sequel-w1a-hugh-bonneville}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe series follows the trials of the management of the fictional Olympic Deliverance Commission (ODC), the body tasked to organise the 2012 London Summer Olympics. Over the series, the ODC have to overcome logistical difficulties, production errors, infrastructure problems and troublesome contributors. The main character is Ian Fletcher, the Head of Deliverance, who is in overall charge of the ODC, and is generally efficient but often has to clean up a PR disaster after the other managers make a mistake. A running thread in series one are the hints that his marriage to a high-flying lawyer is breaking down, which comes to a head in episode six. It is evident that his PA Sally is in love with him, although this remains unspoken.\n\nMeanwhile, Siobhan Sharpe is the excitable, but ultimately clueless Head of Brand through her PR company Perfect Curve. She answers almost every problem with phrases that have almost no substance whatsoever, and never turns her phone off during meetings with the other managers. Consequently, the rest of the managers find her ideas and enthusiastic attitude tiresome, particularly Nick Jowett, Head of Contracts, a blunt Yorkshireman who generally opposes ideas without making alternative suggestions, whilst emphasising that he is from Yorkshire. Jowett briefly becomes Acting Head of Deliverance in Series 2 when Ian Fletcher becomes incapacitated.\n\nKay Hope, Head of Sustainability, is in charge of sorting out what will happen to the buildings, stadia and other Olympic venues after the games. Hope is emphatic that Legacy is something separate from Sustainability although no one makes any attempt to differentiate these two apparently identical areas. She continually mentions that she is a single mother after a bitter divorce, and is paranoid about her public image. In series two Fi Healey joins the team as a new 'Head of Legacy', and instantly becomes Kay's nemesis due to being younger, ambitious and career savvy; the pair constantly clash. Finally, Head of Infrastructure Graham Hitchens gives the impression that he knows everything about the London transport and traffic systems, but is completely ignorant, has no clue about deadlines and frequently upsets various officials.\n\n== Cast ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"72%\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Character \n!! rowspan=\"2\" | Actor\n!! rowspan=\"2\" | Position \n!! colspan=\"2\" | Series\n|-\n! width=\"5%\" | One\n! width=\"5%\" | Two\n|-\n| Ian Fletcher || [[Hugh Bonneville]] || Head of Deliverance of the Olympic Deliverance Commission|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Kay Hope || |[[Amelia Bullmore]] || Head of Sustainability|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n| Sally Owen || [[Olivia Colman]] || Ian Fletcher's personal assistant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Nick Jowett || [[Vincent Franklin]] || Head of Contracts|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Siobhan Sharpe || [[Jessica Hynes]] || Head of Brand|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Graham Hitchins || [[Karl Theobald]] || Head of Infrastructure|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Fi Healey || [[Morven Christie]] || Head of Legacy|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Daniel Stroud || [[Samuel Barnett (actor)|Samuel Barnett]] || Ian Fletcher's personal assistant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Karl Marx|| [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] ||Brand consultant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Recurrent'''\n|-\n|Barney Lumsden|| [[Alex Beckett (actor)|Alex Beckett]] ||Brand consultant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Recurrent'''\n|-\n|Coco Lomax|| [[Sara Pascoe]] ||Brand consultant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Recurrent'''\n|}\n\n==Episodes==\n===Series 1===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|No.\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|Title\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|Overnight viewers\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|Original airdate\n|-\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| Title = Countdown\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|3|14|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 417,000\n| ShortSummary = PR consultant Siobhan Sharpe is preparing to unveil a countdown clock in front of [[Tate Modern]]. However, her boss Ian Fletcher is not impressed. Kay Hope struggles to find a post-games use for the Taekwondo Arena. Meanwhile, Graham Hitchins is planning a new traffic management system, which he decides to test on the day of the clock unveiling.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| Title = Visitors From Rio\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|3|21|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 474,000\n| ShortSummary = The ODC take a group of delegates to meet [[Sebastian Coe|Lord Coe]] at the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|London Olympic Park]]. However, the traffic and a bus driver who doesn't know London conspire against them. Olympic organiser Lord \"Seb\" Coe makes a cameo appearance as himself in this episode.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/mar/11/sebastian-coe-bbc-olympics-spoof | title=Sebastian Coe proves he's game for a laugh in BBC Olympics spoof | last=Frost | first=Vicky | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=11 March 2011 | publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = Roman Remains\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|3|28|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 420,000\n| ShortSummary = After the discovery of Roman remains near the aquatics centre, the building plans need to be modified at the last minute. Meanwhile, Siobhan Sharpe wants the 2012 Games to have their own audio logo.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = Raising The Bar\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|4|4|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 419,000\n| ShortSummary = Former Olympic athlete Dave Wellbeck tours schools as brand ambassador for Raising the Bar, a campaign to get young people interested in the Olympic Games. But his lack of charisma has the opposite effect and Ian Fletcher and Siobhan Sharpe are unsure on how to proceed.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = Cultural Curator\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|4|11|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 389,000\n| ShortSummary =  For the post of Curator of the Cultural Olympiad three applicants are being interviewed. Meanwhile, Sebastian Coe suggests that the Olympic Deliverance Commission team consider entering the London Marathon.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 6\n| Title = Equestrian Controversy\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|4|18|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 432,000\n| ShortSummary = The ODC's plans for the equestrian centre annoy famous film director Tony Ward ([[Tim McInnerny]]), who dumps a pile of horse manure in front of their offices. Ian Fletcher decides to challenge him face-to-face on a Radio 4 ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' interview.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 2===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|No.\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|Title\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|Overnight viewers\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|Original airdate\n|-\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| RTitle = \"Boycott\" \u2013 Part 1\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|3|30|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,200,000\n| ShortSummary = The [[Algeria]]n Olympic team threatens to boycott the Games after discovering that the Shared Belief Centre does not face [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Boycott\u2014Part 1 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01f87cv | work=Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC | date= |accessdate=5 April 2012 }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| RTitle = \"Boycott\" \u2013 Part 2\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|4|6|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 972,000 (overnight)\n| ShortSummary = It is the second half of a very long day. The Algerians issue a deadline of midnight for a solution to their demand for a Shared Belief Centre which faces Mecca, while the French threaten to pull out of the Games if a separate mosque is built. The team have to come up with an idea that will please everyone.<ref>{{cite web | title=Boycott\u2014Part 2 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01flt1g | work=Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC | date= |accessdate=6 April 2012 }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = Clarence House\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|4|13|df=y}}\n| Aux1 =\n| ShortSummary = A decision must be made about the future of the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]], and [[Clarence House]] has asked the ODC to look at ways of linking the 2012 Olympics with the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen's Diamond Jubilee]] \u2013 is 'Jubilympics' the perfect branding solution?<ref>{{cite web | title=Clarence House | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01g7t65 | work=Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC | date= |accessdate=6 April 2012 }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = The Rapper\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|4|20|df=y}}\n| Aux1 =\n| ShortSummary = Siobhan's team design a major sexual health campaign, complete with a rap song \"Get It On\", which may upset the Catholic competitors.\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = Catastrophisation\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|7|10|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,450,000\n| ShortSummary = Thirty two days to go, and with Head of Deliverance Ian Fletcher chairing the final ever meeting of the Twenty Twelve Security Committee's Special Catastrophisation Unit, it emerges that someone has been caught converting official Olympic starting pistols to fire live rounds; with the US Security Forward Team about to arrive.\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 6\n| Title = Inclusivity Day\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|7|17|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,800,000\n| ShortSummary = Having been shot in the foot with a doctored starting pistol, Ian Fletcher discovers that he is also shortly to be without a PA as current PA Daniel Stroud has been offered another job. Back over at the offices of the ODC, they try to work out how to launch Inclusivity Day in London on the same day that Seb Coe is launching Diversity Day in [[Oldham]], when even though both Boris Johnson and Baroness [[Tanni Grey-Thompson]] have agreed to take part, no-one knows what Inclusivity Day is. Meanwhile, over at PR company Perfect Curve, Siobhan Sharpe and her team devise a viral campaign designed to change the face of women's football without mentioning women's football following catastrophic ticket sales.\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 7\n| Title = Loose Ends\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|7|24|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,780,000\n| ShortSummary = Ten days left to try to tie up loose ends before the Deliverance Team finally hands over to the Live Team, the main problem being that the opening ceremony fireworks display will launch the ground-to-air missiles installed to protect the Games, and newly divorced and soon-to-be redundant Ian must decide what to do about Sally. The programme ends just before he expresses his feelings...\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n|}\n\n==Reviews==\n===Critical reviews===\nReviews for episode 1 were mixed, commenting that it was milder in its satire than they expected; Ed Cumming in ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' stated \"Perhaps it just needs some time to settle. Though it was very funny in parts, the first episode of ''Twenty Twelve'' suggests that the series, like the actual cost of the Olympics, might hit slightly wide of its ample target.\"<ref>{{cite news | first=Ed | last=Cumming | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8382862/Twenty-Twelve-BBC-Four-review.html | title=''Twenty Twelve'', BBC Four, review | work=Daily Telegraph | date=15 March 2011 }}</ref> Likewise, Sam Wollaston in ''[[The Guardian]]'' suggested that due to the participation of Seb Coe it was \"on song\": \"Biting satire this isn't. It's nibbling satire, delivered by [[Garra Rufa]] fish...''[[The Thick of It]]'' is a lot more entertaining...I don't think that politicians were removing their shoes, rolling up their trousers and queuing up for cameos in ''The Thick of It''\".<ref>{{cite news | first=Sam | last=Wollaston | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/mar/14/twenty-twelve-tv-review | title=TV review: Twenty Twelve; The Secret War on Terror | work=The Guardian | date=14 March 2011 }}</ref> Brian Viner, writing in ''[[The Independent]]'' was more impressed by Coe's cameo; \"There is surely no other country in the world that would laugh at itself in this way, even persuading the vast project's principal mover-and-shaker, in our case the Rt Hon Lord Coe KBE, to participate in the joke\". He went on to commend the series \"...I was hooked anyway, by the mischief in John Morton's script and the beautifully nuanced performances of, in particular, Hugh Bonneville and Jessica Hynes\".<ref>{{cite news | first=Brian | last=Viner | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv--twenty-twelve-bbc4-the-secret-war-on-terror-bbc2-2241805.html | title=Last Night's TV \u2013 Twenty Twelve, BBC4; The Secret War on Terror, BBC2 | work=The Independent | date=15 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBrian Viner, reviewing the series as a whole stated the series was \"always amusing and sporadically very funny... It's hard to think of a spoof documentary that has been more fortuitously timed than ''Twenty Twelve''.\"<ref>{{cite news | first=Brian | last=Viner | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv--the-reckoning-itv1-twenty-twelve-bbc4-2269595.html | title=Last Night's TV \u2013 ''The Reckoning'', ITV1; ''Twenty Twelve'', BBC4 | work=The Independent | date=19 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Real-life similarities===\nIt was widely commented upon in the press that the day after the broadcast of the first episode, which features problems with the 1,000-day countdown clock, the real-life clock in [[Trafalgar Square]] broke soon after it had been launched by [[Sebastian Coe|Lord Coe]] and London mayor [[Boris Johnson]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/mar/15/london-2012-olympics-clock-stops | title=London 2012 Olympics countdown clock stops | first=Owen | last=Gibson | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=15 March 2011 | publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] }}</ref>\n\nAn additional coincidence occurred when some of the first athletes to arrive in London for the Olympics suffered delays; their bus drivers were unfamiliar with London and unable to find the Olympic Park in scenes that closely resembled the plot of episode 2.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/9403023/London-2012-Olympics-American-and-Australian-team-buses-get-lost-from-Heathrow-to-Olympic-Park.html | title=London 2012 Olympics: American and Australian team buses get lost from Heathrow to Olympic Park | first=Jacquelin | last=Magnay | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=16 July 2012 | publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] }}</ref>\n\n===''The Games'' plagiarism accusation===\n''Twenty Twelve'' has been criticised as bearing a strong resemblance to the Australian mockumentary series ''[[The Games (Australian TV series)|The Games]]'', a similar series set before the 2000 Sydney Olympics.<ref name=\"adc\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/45014.html | title=How television works: a heart-warming story for all the family | date=11 March 2011 | last1=Clarke | first1=John | last2=Stevenson | first2=Ross \n|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n}}</ref> Writer of ''The Games'' [[John Clarke (satirist)|John Clarke]] said, \"We worked very hard on that project and we had long conversations with these people who've now done a show like that in Britain\".<ref name=\"Quin\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/bbc-imitation-no-flattery-clarke-20110315-1bvx4.html | title=BBC imitation no flattery: Clarke | first=Karl | last=Quin | work=[[The Age]] | date=16 March 2011 | publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] }}</ref><ref name=\"Quin\" /><ref name=\"Plunkett\">{{cite news | last=Plunkett | first=John | title=BBC denies Olympics comedy stole from Australian TV show | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/mar/16/bbc-olympics-comedy-twenty-twelve | newspaper=The Guardian | date=16 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe BBC denied claims of plagiarism. \"It is a very different show, the only similarities between them are that they are both set around the Olympics,\" a corporation source said.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8381341/BBC-in-plagiarism-row-over-Australian-Olympics-show-copy-claims.html | title=BBC in plagiarism row over 'Australian Olympics show copy claims' | first=Andrew | last=Hough | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=15 March 2011 | publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|TMG]] }}</ref>  Clarke's own website later made a reference to the dispute by describing himself and writing partner as \"run[ning] a charitable institute supplying formats to British television\".<ref>{{cite web | last=Clarke | first=John | title=The Games | url=http://mrjohnclarke.com/projects/the-games | work=MrJohnClarke | date= | accessdate=9 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nThe programme was the winner of the Best Sitcom category at the [[British Comedy Awards]] 2011,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/00000711/british_comedy_awards_2011_winners_list/ | title=British Comedy Awards 2011 | date=16 December 2011 }}</ref> while Jessica Hynes received the Best Comedy Performance award for her role from the [[Royal Television Society]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2013/03/20/17465/gold_for_hynes! | title=Gold for Hynes! | publisher=Chortle | date= | accessdate=22 March 2013 }}</ref> For his role in ''Twenty Twelve'' Osy Ikhile was nominated for \"Best TV Comedy Performance\" at the Black International Film Festival and Music Video & Screen Awards.<ref name=\"biffbbc\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/eastenders/2012/10/eastenders-up-for-four-mvsas.shtml | title=EastEnders up for four MVSAs | publisher=[[BBC Online]] | work=EastEnders | date=4 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, the programme was awarded title of 'Best Sitcom' at the annual [[BAFTA]] awards, with star [[Olivia Colman]] also picking up the award for 'Best Female Comedy Performance', a category in which co-star [[Jessica Hynes]] was also nominated. [[Hugh Bonneville]] also received a nomination for his role of Head of Deliverance, Ian Fletcher.<ref name=Olivia>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-22484527 | title=Olivia Colman wins two Bafta awards | work=BBC News | date=12 May 2013 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Nominee\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Result\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Reference\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2011\n|rowspan=3|[[British Comedy Awards]]\n|[[John Morton (writer)|John Morton]]\n|Best TV Sitcom\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=3|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|[[Hugh Bonneville]]\n|Best TV Comedy Actor\n|rowspan=2 {{nominated}}\n|-\n|John Morton\n|Best New Comedy Programme\n|-\n|rowspan=7|2012\n|rowspan=2|[[British Academy Television Awards 2012|BAFTA TV Award]]\n|[[Olivia Colman]]\n|Best Female Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|rowspan=2 {{nominated}}\n|rowspan=2|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|Hugh Bonneville\n|Best Male Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[British Comedy Awards]]\n|''Twenty Twelve''\n|Best Sitcom\n|rowspan=4 {{nominated}}\n|rowspan=4|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|Hugh Bonneville\n|Best TV Comedy Actor\n|-\n|[[Jessica Hynes]]\n|rowspan=2|Best TV Comedy Actress\n|-\n|Olivia Colman\n|-\n|[[Broadcasting Press Guild Awards]]\n|John Morton, Paul Schlesinger\n|Best Comedy/Entertainment\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|rowspan=9|2013\n|rowspan=5|[[British Academy Television Awards 2013|BAFTA TV Award]]\n|Olivia Colman\n|Best Female Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=5|<ref name=awards>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1861225/awards?ref_=tt_awd |title=Twenty Twelve Awards |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=imdb.com |publisher= |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n|-\n|John Morton, Paul Schlesinger, Catherine Gosling Fuller, [[Jon Plowman]]\n|Best Situation Comedy\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|John Morton\n|Best Writer: Comedy\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|Jessica Hynes\n|Best Female Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|Hugh Bonneville\n|Best Male Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Broadcasting Press Guild Awards]]\n|rowspan=2|John Morton\n|Best Comedy/Entertainment\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=2|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|Writer's Award\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Royal Television Society|RTS Television Awards]]\n|Jessica Hynes\n|Best Comedy Performance\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=2|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|John Morton\n|Best Writer - Comedy\n|{{nominated}}\n|}\n\n==DVD release==\nOn 23 October 2012 BBC Home Entertainment released the entire series in a two-disc [[DVD]] set.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Twenty-Twelve-DVDs-Announced/17509 | title=Twenty Twelve - The BBC Comedy Series is Now Scheduled with a Street Date | last=Lambert | first=David | date=19 September 2012 | work=[[TVShowsOnDVD.com]] | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922095319/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Twenty-Twelve-DVDs-Announced/17509 | archivedate=22 September 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|W1A (TV series)}}\nAfter the final episode had aired, there was speculation in the media about a third series with the team liaising with the organisation team of the [[Rio de Janeiro]] games in 2016, or becoming management consultants.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/film_and_tv/tv/article1088609.ece | title=Games for a laugh | first=Stephen | last=Armstrong | work=[[The Sunday Times]] Culture Magazine | date=29 July 2012 | publisher=[[Times Newspapers Ltd]] }} (Subscription required)</ref> When asked about whether the hit show could return, main star [[Hugh Bonneville|Bonneville]] said,  \"Absolutely. They could go and help with the organisation of the Rio Games in 2016...but ultimately, this is a crack team that could go anywhere and manage anything \u2013 the City, say, or the armed services. The NHS also needs rebranding. They could get Ian in to announce, 'If health is about anything, it's about managing expectations. We have got to get people to appreciate there are a lot of positive things about ill health. We need to make it sexy'.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Rampton | first=James | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/twenty-twelve-back-on-track-with-hugh-bonneville-the-lord-of-office-jargon-7594951.html | title=Twenty Twelve: Back on track with Hugh Bonneville, the lord of office jargon | newspaper=The Independent | date=29 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA sequel was announced by the BBC in late 2013 and broadcast March 19 to April 9, 2014. Named ''[[W1A (TV series)|W1A]]'', it follows Ian Fletcher (Bonneville) and Siobhan Sharpe ([[Jessica Hynes]]) as they pursue new careers as part of the BBC management team.  A second series was commissioned in September 2014 and broadcast April 23 to May 14, 2015.  A third series began airing on 18 September 2017.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Olympic Delivery Authority]]\n* [[London Organising Committee of the Olympic Games and Paralympic Games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{British Comedy Guide|tv|twenty_twelve|Twenty Twelve}}\n*{{IMDb title|1861225|Twenty Twelve}}\n\n{{BAFTA TV Award for Best Situation Comedy 2000\u20132019}}\n\n[[Category:2011 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2012 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:BBC television comedy]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British mockumentary television series]]\n[[Category:TV series involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|2012 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Twenty Twelve\n| image = Twenty Twelve.jpg\n| composer =\n| genre = [[Mockumentary]]\n| writer = [[John Morton (writer)|John Morton]]\n| director = John Morton\n| creator = John Morton\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| starring = [[Hugh Bonneville]]<br />[[Jessica Hynes]]<br />[[Amelia Bullmore]]<br />[[Olivia Colman]]<br />[[Vincent Franklin]]<br />[[Karl Theobald]]<br />[[Morven Christie]]\n| narrated = [[David Tennant]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Irving Berlin]]\n| opentheme = \"[[Let's Face the Music and Dance]]\" sung by [[Nat King Cole]]\n| company = [[BBC]]\n| editor =\n| executive_producer = [[Jon Plowman]]\n| producer = Paul Schlesinger\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| picture_format = ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]) [[576i]]<br />([[High-definition television|HDTV]]) [[1080i]]\n| audio_format = Stereo\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2011|3|14|df=y}}\n| last_aired =  {{End date|2012|7|24|df=y}}\n| num_series = 2\n| num_episodes = 13\n| list_episodes =\n| network = [[BBC Four]] (2011\u20132012)<br />[[BBC Two]] (2012)<br />[[BBC HD]]\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          =''[[W1A (TV series)|W1A]]''\n| website = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01f87nh\n}}\n'''''Twenty Twelve''''' is a [[BBC]] television comedy series written and directed by [[John Morton (writer)|John Morton]]. Starring [[Hugh Bonneville]], [[Jessica Hynes]] and [[Amelia Bullmore]], the programme is a spoof on-location documentary (or [[mockumentary]]) following the organisation of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]]. It was first broadcast on UK television station [[BBC Four]] in March 2011 to coincide with the 500-day countdown to the opening ceremony.\n\n''Twenty Twelve'' gained mainly positive reviews from critics, and a four-part second series was announced on 15 April 2011,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2011/04_april/15/twentytwelve.shtml | title=BBC Four recommissions hit comedy series Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC Press Office | date=15 April 2011 }}</ref> which began airing on 30 March 2012 on BBC Two.<ref>{{cite news | title=The British Comedy award-winning Twenty Twelve returns tonight for a four-part second series. | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2012/13/twenty-twelve.html | date= | accessdate=17 March 2012 | publisher=BBC Press Office }}</ref> A further three episodes of series 2 began airing from 10 July 2012.<ref>{{cite news | last=Mickel | first=Andrew | title='Twenty Twelve' gets third series | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a356455/twenty-twelve-gets-third-series.html | newspaper=Digital Spy | date=17 December 2011 }}</ref> The series' last episode was broadcast on 24 July 2012, three days before the opening ceremony of the London Olympic Games. \n\nSeveral core characters went on to appear in a sequel, [[W1A_(TV_series)|W1A]], in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/dec/05/bbc-twenty-twelve-sequel-w1a-hugh-bonneville}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe series follows the trials of the management of the fictional Olympic Deliverance Commission (ODC), the body tasked to organise the 2012 London Summer Olympics. Over the series, the ODC have to overcome logistical difficulties, production errors, infrastructure problems and troublesome contributors. The main character is Ian Fletcher, the Head of Deliverance, who is in overall charge of the ODC, and is generally efficient but often has to clean up a PR disaster after the other managers make a mistake. A running thread in series one are the hints that his marriage to a high-flying lawyer is breaking down, which comes to a head in episode six. It is evident that his PA Sally is in love with him, although this remains unspoken.\n\nMeanwhile, Siobhan Sharpe is the excitable, but ultimately clueless Head of Brand through her PR company Perfect Curve. She answers almost every problem with phrases that have almost no substance whatsoever, and never turns her phone off during meetings with the other managers. Consequently, the rest of the managers find her ideas and enthusiastic attitude tiresome, particularly Nick Jowett, Head of Contracts, a blunt Yorkshireman who generally opposes ideas without making alternative suggestions, whilst emphasising that he is from Yorkshire. Jowett briefly becomes Acting Head of Deliverance in Series 2 when Ian Fletcher becomes incapacitated.\n\nKay Hope, Head of Sustainability, is in charge of sorting out what will happen to the buildings, stadia and other Olympic venues after the games. Hope is emphatic that Legacy is something separate from Sustainability although no one makes any attempt to differentiate these two apparently identical areas. She continually mentions that she is a single mother after a bitter divorce, and is paranoid about her public image. In series two Fi Healey joins the team as a new 'Head of Legacy', and instantly becomes Kay's nemesis due to being younger, ambitious and career savvy; the pair constantly clash. Finally, Head of Infrastructure Graham Hitchens gives the impression that he knows everything about the London transport and traffic systems, but is completely ignorant, has no clue about deadlines and frequently upsets various officials.\n\n== Cast ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"72%\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Character \n!! rowspan=\"2\" | Actor\n!! rowspan=\"2\" | Position \n!! colspan=\"2\" | Series\n|-\n! width=\"5%\" | One\n! width=\"5%\" | Two\n|-\n| Ian Fletcher || [[Hugh Bonneville]] || Head of Deliverance of the Olympic Deliverance Commission|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Kay Hope || |[[Amelia Bullmore]] || Head of Sustainability|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n| Sally Owen || [[Olivia Colman]] || Ian Fletcher's personal assistant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Nick Jowett || [[Vincent Franklin]] || Head of Contracts|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Siobhan Sharpe || [[Jessica Hynes]] || Head of Brand|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Graham Hitchins || [[Karl Theobald]] || Head of Infrastructure|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Fi Healey || [[Morven Christie]] || Head of Legacy|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Daniel Stroud || [[Samuel Barnett (actor)|Samuel Barnett]] || Ian Fletcher's personal assistant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Main'''\n|-\n|Karl Marx|| [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] ||Brand consultant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Recurrent'''\n|-\n|Barney Lumsden|| [[Alex Beckett (actor)|Alex Beckett]] ||Brand consultant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Recurrent'''\n|-\n|Coco Lomax|| [[Sara Pascoe]] ||Brand consultant|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#dfd; text-align:center;\" | '''Recurrent'''\n|}\n\n==Episodes==\n===Series 1===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|No.\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|Title\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|Overnight viewers\n! style = \"background: #7B8FF6;\"|Original airdate\n|-\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| Title = Countdown\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|3|14|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 417,000\n| ShortSummary = PR consultant Siobhan Sharpe is preparing to unveil a countdown clock in front of [[Tate Modern]]. However, her boss Ian Fletcher is not impressed. Kay Hope struggles to find a post-games use for the Taekwondo Arena. Meanwhile, Graham Hitchins is planning a new traffic management system, which he decides to test on the day of the clock unveiling.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| Title = Visitors From Rio\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|3|21|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 474,000\n| ShortSummary = The ODC take a group of delegates to meet [[Sebastian Coe|Lord Coe]] at the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|London Olympic Park]]. However, the traffic and a bus driver who doesn't know London conspire against them. Olympic organiser Lord \"Seb\" Coe makes a cameo appearance as himself in this episode.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/mar/11/sebastian-coe-bbc-olympics-spoof | title=Sebastian Coe proves he's game for a laugh in BBC Olympics spoof | last=Frost | first=Vicky | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=11 March 2011 | publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = Roman Remains\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|3|28|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 420,000\n| ShortSummary = After the discovery of Roman remains near the aquatics centre, the building plans need to be modified at the last minute. Meanwhile, Siobhan Sharpe wants the 2012 Games to have their own audio logo.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = Raising The Bar\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|4|4|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 419,000\n| ShortSummary = Former Olympic athlete Dave Wellbeck tours schools as brand ambassador for Raising the Bar, a campaign to get young people interested in the Olympic Games. But his lack of charisma has the opposite effect and Ian Fletcher and Siobhan Sharpe are unsure on how to proceed.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = Cultural Curator\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|4|11|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 389,000\n| ShortSummary =  For the post of Curator of the Cultural Olympiad three applicants are being interviewed. Meanwhile, Sebastian Coe suggests that the Olympic Deliverance Commission team consider entering the London Marathon.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 6\n| Title = Equestrian Controversy\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|4|18|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 432,000\n| ShortSummary = The ODC's plans for the equestrian centre annoy famous film director Tony Ward ([[Tim McInnerny]]), who dumps a pile of horse manure in front of their offices. Ian Fletcher decides to challenge him face-to-face on a Radio 4 ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' interview.\n| LineColor = #7B8FF6\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 2===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|No.\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|Title\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|Overnight viewers\n! style = \"background: #F7C121;\"|Original airdate\n|-\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| RTitle = \"Boycott\" \u2013 Part 1\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|3|30|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,200,000\n| ShortSummary = The [[Algeria]]n Olympic team threatens to boycott the Games after discovering that the Shared Belief Centre does not face [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Boycott\u2014Part 1 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01f87cv | work=Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC | date= |accessdate=5 April 2012 }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| RTitle = \"Boycott\" \u2013 Part 2\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|4|6|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 972,000 (overnight)\n| ShortSummary = It is the second half of a very long day. The Algerians issue a deadline of midnight for a solution to their demand for a Shared Belief Centre which faces Mecca, while the French threaten to pull out of the Games if a separate mosque is built. The team have to come up with an idea that will please everyone.<ref>{{cite web | title=Boycott\u2014Part 2 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01flt1g | work=Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC | date= |accessdate=6 April 2012 }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = Clarence House\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|4|13|df=y}}\n| Aux1 =\n| ShortSummary = A decision must be made about the future of the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]], and [[Clarence House]] has asked the ODC to look at ways of linking the 2012 Olympics with the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen's Diamond Jubilee]] \u2013 is 'Jubilympics' the perfect branding solution?<ref>{{cite web | title=Clarence House | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01g7t65 | work=Twenty Twelve | publisher=BBC | date= |accessdate=6 April 2012 }}</ref>\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = The Rapper\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|4|20|df=y}}\n| Aux1 =\n| ShortSummary = Siobhan's team design a major sexual health campaign, complete with a rap song \"Get It On\", which may upset the Catholic competitors.\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = Catastrophisation\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|7|10|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,450,000\n| ShortSummary = Thirty two days to go, and with Head of Deliverance Ian Fletcher chairing the final ever meeting of the Twenty Twelve Security Committee's Special Catastrophisation Unit, it emerges that someone has been caught converting official Olympic starting pistols to fire live rounds; with the US Security Forward Team about to arrive.\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 6\n| Title = Inclusivity Day\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|7|17|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,800,000\n| ShortSummary = Having been shot in the foot with a doctored starting pistol, Ian Fletcher discovers that he is also shortly to be without a PA as current PA Daniel Stroud has been offered another job. Back over at the offices of the ODC, they try to work out how to launch Inclusivity Day in London on the same day that Seb Coe is launching Diversity Day in [[Oldham]], when even though both Boris Johnson and Baroness [[Tanni Grey-Thompson]] have agreed to take part, no-one knows what Inclusivity Day is. Meanwhile, over at PR company Perfect Curve, Siobhan Sharpe and her team devise a viral campaign designed to change the face of women's football without mentioning women's football following catastrophic ticket sales.\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 7\n| Title = Loose Ends\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|7|24|df=y}}\n| Aux1 = 1,780,000\n| ShortSummary = Ten days left to try to tie up loose ends before the Deliverance Team finally hands over to the Live Team, the main problem being that the opening ceremony fireworks display will launch the ground-to-air missiles installed to protect the Games, and newly divorced and soon-to-be redundant Ian must decide what to do about Sally. The programme ends just before he expresses his feelings...\n| LineColor = #F7C121\n}}\n|}\n\n==Reviews==\n===Critical reviews===\nReviews for episode 1 were mixed, commenting that it was milder in its satire than they expected; Ed Cumming in ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' stated \"Perhaps it just needs some time to settle. Though it was very funny in parts, the first episode of ''Twenty Twelve'' suggests that the series, like the actual cost of the Olympics, might hit slightly wide of its ample target.\"<ref>{{cite news | first=Ed | last=Cumming | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8382862/Twenty-Twelve-BBC-Four-review.html | title=''Twenty Twelve'', BBC Four, review | work=Daily Telegraph | date=15 March 2011 }}</ref> Likewise, Sam Wollaston in ''[[The Guardian]]'' suggested that due to the participation of Seb Coe it was \"on song\": \"Biting satire this isn't. It's nibbling satire, delivered by [[Garra Rufa]] fish...''[[The Thick of It]]'' is a lot more entertaining...I don't think that politicians were removing their shoes, rolling up their trousers and queuing up for cameos in ''The Thick of It''\".<ref>{{cite news | first=Sam | last=Wollaston | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/mar/14/twenty-twelve-tv-review | title=TV review: Twenty Twelve; The Secret War on Terror | work=The Guardian | date=14 March 2011 }}</ref> Brian Viner, writing in ''[[The Independent]]'' was more impressed by Coe's cameo; \"There is surely no other country in the world that would laugh at itself in this way, even persuading the vast project's principal mover-and-shaker, in our case the Rt Hon Lord Coe KBE, to participate in the joke\". He went on to commend the series \"...I was hooked anyway, by the mischief in John Morton's script and the beautifully nuanced performances of, in particular, Hugh Bonneville and Jessica Hynes\".<ref>{{cite news | first=Brian | last=Viner | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv--twenty-twelve-bbc4-the-secret-war-on-terror-bbc2-2241805.html | title=Last Night's TV \u2013 Twenty Twelve, BBC4; The Secret War on Terror, BBC2 | work=The Independent | date=15 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBrian Viner, reviewing the series as a whole stated the series was \"always amusing and sporadically very funny... It's hard to think of a spoof documentary that has been more fortuitously timed than ''Twenty Twelve''.\"<ref>{{cite news | first=Brian | last=Viner | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv--the-reckoning-itv1-twenty-twelve-bbc4-2269595.html | title=Last Night's TV \u2013 ''The Reckoning'', ITV1; ''Twenty Twelve'', BBC4 | work=The Independent | date=19 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Real-life similarities===\nIt was widely commented upon in the press that the day after the broadcast of the first episode, which features problems with the 1,000-day countdown clock, the real-life clock in [[Trafalgar Square]] broke soon after it had been launched by [[Sebastian Coe|Lord Coe]] and London mayor [[Boris Johnson]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/mar/15/london-2012-olympics-clock-stops | title=London 2012 Olympics countdown clock stops | first=Owen | last=Gibson | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=15 March 2011 | publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] }}</ref>\n\nAn additional coincidence occurred when some of the first athletes to arrive in London for the Olympics suffered delays; their bus drivers were unfamiliar with London and unable to find the Olympic Park in scenes that closely resembled the plot of episode 2.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/9403023/London-2012-Olympics-American-and-Australian-team-buses-get-lost-from-Heathrow-to-Olympic-Park.html | title=London 2012 Olympics: American and Australian team buses get lost from Heathrow to Olympic Park | first=Jacquelin | last=Magnay | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=16 July 2012 | publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] }}</ref>\n\n===''The Games'' plagiarism accusation===\n''Twenty Twelve'' has been criticised as bearing a strong resemblance to the Australian mockumentary series ''[[The Games (Australian TV series)|The Games]]'', a similar series set before the 2000 Sydney Olympics.<ref name=\"adc\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/45014.html | title=How television works: a heart-warming story for all the family | date=11 March 2011 | last1=Clarke | first1=John | last2=Stevenson | first2=Ross \n|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n}}</ref> Writer of ''The Games'' [[John Clarke (satirist)|John Clarke]] said, \"We worked very hard on that project and we had long conversations with these people who've now done a show like that in Britain\".<ref name=\"Quin\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/bbc-imitation-no-flattery-clarke-20110315-1bvx4.html | title=BBC imitation no flattery: Clarke | first=Karl | last=Quin | work=[[The Age]] | date=16 March 2011 | publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] }}</ref><ref name=\"Quin\" /><ref name=\"Plunkett\">{{cite news | last=Plunkett | first=John | title=BBC denies Olympics comedy stole from Australian TV show | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/mar/16/bbc-olympics-comedy-twenty-twelve | newspaper=The Guardian | date=16 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe BBC denied claims of plagiarism. \"It is a very different show, the only similarities between them are that they are both set around the Olympics,\" a corporation source said.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8381341/BBC-in-plagiarism-row-over-Australian-Olympics-show-copy-claims.html | title=BBC in plagiarism row over 'Australian Olympics show copy claims' | first=Andrew | last=Hough | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=15 March 2011 | publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|TMG]] }}</ref>  Clarke's own website later made a reference to the dispute by describing himself and writing partner as \"run[ning] a charitable institute supplying formats to British television\".<ref>{{cite web | last=Clarke | first=John | title=The Games | url=http://mrjohnclarke.com/projects/the-games | work=MrJohnClarke | date= | accessdate=9 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nThe programme was the winner of the Best Sitcom category at the [[British Comedy Awards]] 2011,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/00000711/british_comedy_awards_2011_winners_list/ | title=British Comedy Awards 2011 | date=16 December 2011 }}</ref> while Jessica Hynes received the Best Comedy Performance award for her role from the [[Royal Television Society]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2013/03/20/17465/gold_for_hynes! | title=Gold for Hynes! | publisher=Chortle | date= | accessdate=22 March 2013 }}</ref> For his role in ''Twenty Twelve'' Osy Ikhile was nominated for \"Best TV Comedy Performance\" at the Black International Film Festival and Music Video & Screen Awards.<ref name=\"biffbbc\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/eastenders/2012/10/eastenders-up-for-four-mvsas.shtml | title=EastEnders up for four MVSAs | publisher=[[BBC Online]] | work=EastEnders | date=4 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, the programme was awarded title of 'Best Sitcom' at the annual [[BAFTA]] awards, with star [[Olivia Colman]] also picking up the award for 'Best Female Comedy Performance', a category in which co-star [[Jessica Hynes]] was also nominated. [[Hugh Bonneville]] also received a nomination for his role of Head of Deliverance, Ian Fletcher.<ref name=Olivia>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-22484527 | title=Olivia Colman wins two Bafta awards | work=BBC News | date=12 May 2013 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Nominee\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Result\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Reference\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2011\n|rowspan=3|[[British Comedy Awards]]\n|[[John Morton (writer)|John Morton]]\n|Best TV Sitcom\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=3|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|[[Hugh Bonneville]]\n|Best TV Comedy Actor\n|rowspan=2 {{nominated}}\n|-\n|John Morton\n|Best New Comedy Programme\n|-\n|rowspan=7|2012\n|rowspan=2|[[British Academy Television Awards 2012|BAFTA TV Award]]\n|[[Olivia Colman]]\n|Best Female Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|rowspan=2 {{nominated}}\n|rowspan=2|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|Hugh Bonneville\n|Best Male Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[British Comedy Awards]]\n|''Twenty Twelve''\n|Best Sitcom\n|rowspan=4 {{nominated}}\n|rowspan=4|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|Hugh Bonneville\n|Best TV Comedy Actor\n|-\n|[[Jessica Hynes]]\n|rowspan=2|Best TV Comedy Actress\n|-\n|Olivia Colman\n|-\n|[[Broadcasting Press Guild Awards]]\n|John Morton, Paul Schlesinger\n|Best Comedy/Entertainment\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|rowspan=9|2013\n|rowspan=5|[[British Academy Television Awards 2013|BAFTA TV Award]]\n|Olivia Colman\n|Best Female Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=5|<ref name=awards>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1861225/awards?ref_=tt_awd |title=Twenty Twelve Awards |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=imdb.com |publisher= |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n|-\n|John Morton, Paul Schlesinger, Catherine Gosling Fuller, [[Jon Plowman]]\n|Best Situation Comedy\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|John Morton\n|Best Writer: Comedy\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|Jessica Hynes\n|Best Female Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|Hugh Bonneville\n|Best Male Performance in a Comedy Programme\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Broadcasting Press Guild Awards]]\n|rowspan=2|John Morton\n|Best Comedy/Entertainment\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=2|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|Writer's Award\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Royal Television Society|RTS Television Awards]]\n|Jessica Hynes\n|Best Comedy Performance\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=2|<ref name=awards />\n|-\n|John Morton\n|Best Writer - Comedy\n|{{nominated}}\n|}\n\n==DVD release==\nOn 23 October 2012 BBC Home Entertainment released the entire series in a two-disc [[DVD]] set.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Twenty-Twelve-DVDs-Announced/17509 | title=Twenty Twelve - The BBC Comedy Series is Now Scheduled with a Street Date | last=Lambert | first=David | date=19 September 2012 | work=[[TVShowsOnDVD.com]] | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922095319/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Twenty-Twelve-DVDs-Announced/17509 | archivedate=22 September 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|W1A (TV series)}}\nAfter the final episode had aired, there was speculation in the media about a third series with the team liaising with the organisation team of the [[Rio de Janeiro]] games in 2016, or becoming management consultants.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/film_and_tv/tv/article1088609.ece | title=Games for a laugh | first=Stephen | last=Armstrong | work=[[The Sunday Times]] Culture Magazine | date=29 July 2012 | publisher=[[Times Newspapers Ltd]] }} (Subscription required)</ref> When asked about whether the hit show could return, main star [[Hugh Bonneville|Bonneville]] said,  \"Absolutely. They could go and help with the organisation of the Rio Games in 2016...but ultimately, this is a crack team that could go anywhere and manage anything \u2013 the City, say, or the armed services. The NHS also needs rebranding. They could get Ian in to announce, 'If health is about anything, it's about managing expectations. We have got to get people to appreciate there are a lot of positive things about ill health. We need to make it sexy'.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Rampton | first=James | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/twenty-twelve-back-on-track-with-hugh-bonneville-the-lord-of-office-jargon-7594951.html | title=Twenty Twelve: Back on track with Hugh Bonneville, the lord of office jargon | newspaper=The Independent | date=29 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA sequel was announced by the BBC in late 2013 and broadcast March 19 to April 9, 2014. Named ''[[W1A (TV series)|W1A]]'', it follows Ian Fletcher (Bonneville) and Siobhan Sharpe ([[Jessica Hynes]]) as they pursue new careers as part of the BBC management team.  A second series was commissioned in September 2014 and broadcast April 23 to May 14, 2015.  A third series began airing on 18 September 2017.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Olympic Delivery Authority]]\n* [[London Organising Committee of the Olympic Games and Paralympic Games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{British Comedy Guide|tv|twenty_twelve|Twenty Twelve}}\n*{{IMDb title|1861225|Twenty Twelve}}\n\n{{BAFTA TV Award for Best Situation Comedy 2000\u20132019}}\n\n[[Category:2011 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2012 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British satirical television series]]\n[[Category:2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:BBC television comedy]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British mockumentary television series]]\n[[Category:TV series involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Mythlike-Cell", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twenty_Twelve"}
{"title_page": "Mati Zata", "text_new": "{{short description|Zimbabwean footballer}}\n{{notability|Sport|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mati Zata\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Matifadza Zata\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|06|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Zimbabwe]]\n| height = 1.79m\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Free Agent]]\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 2012\u20132013\n| youthclubs1 = [[Alloa Athletic]]\n| youthyears2 = 2013\u20132018\n| youthclubs2 = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n| youthyears3 = 2018\u20132019\n| youthclubs3 = [[Dundee United]]\n| years1 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs1 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps1 = 0\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[East Kilbride F.C.|East Kilbride]] (loan)\n| caps2 = \n| goals2 = \n| years3 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs3 = [[Dundee United]]\n| caps3 = 0\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2019\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Tayport F.C.|Tayport]] (loan)\n| caps4 = \n| goals4 = \n| years5 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs5 = [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n| caps5 = 3\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Rossvale F.C.|Rossvale]] (loan)\n| caps6 = \n| goals6 = \n| nationalyears1 = 2017\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2019-\n| nationalteam2 = [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe U23]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| club-update = 22:51, 11 April 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 10:17, 10 August 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Mati Zata''' (born 23 June 2000) is a Zimbabwean footballer [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]] who last played for [[Scottish League One]] club [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]].\n\n==Early life==\nZata, originally from [[Zimbabwe]], moved to Scotland at 4 years of age, living in [[Alloa]], Scotland with his family. He has represented his country of [[Zimbabwe]] at [[Zimbabwe national football team|under-23 level]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Alloa Athletic===\nZata joined the youth system at [[Alloa Athletic]] in 2012. He and made his under-20s debut for the club before his 13th birthday. Zata's footballing ability quickly caught the eye of Scottish Premier league club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] after only a year at [[Alloa Athletic]].\n\n===Rangers===\nIn 2013, he joined Rangers, scoring 24 goals in his first year as a midfielder at the club. Zata quickly established himself as an important member of the Rangers youth Academy. During his time at Rangers, Zata was called up to represent the Scottish National Team under 16s. Zata earned a 2-year scholarship whilst at the club at 16 years old and also went on loan to lowland league club [[East Kilbride F.C.|East Kilbride]] to gain valuable first team experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/local-sport/rangers-kid-mati-zata-i-11121210|title=Rangers kid Mati Zata: \"I want to make a name for myself at East Kilbride\"|first=Paul|last=Thomson|date=7 September 2017|website=dailyrecord}}</ref>\n\n===Dundee United===\nIn 2018, Zata joined [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on an 18-month contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/dundee-united-sign-former-rangers-12092095|title=Dundee United sign former Rangers youngster Mati Zata|date=26 February 2018|website=Daily Record|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> During this time Zata captained the reserve side to victory in the Oban Cup. Zata earned his debut in a [[2018&ndash;19 Scottish Challenge Cup]] tie with [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone under-20s]], making a substitute appearance after only two minutes. Zata earned praise from the club's supporters after his debut match due to his combative style in midfield which helped the team come from behind to win the match 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/5739/ZATA-ZONES-IN-ON-GREATER-INVOLVEMENT.html|title=Zata zones in on greater involvement|website=Dundee United Football Club|date=16 August 2018|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> Zata made his second appearance for the club in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Alloa Athletic]] in the same competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/long-term-injury-makes-dundee-united-captains-heart-fonder-for-the-game/|title=Long-term injury makes Dundee United captain's heart fonder for the game|newspaper=Evening Telegraph|date=12 September 2018|accessdate=29 August 2019|first=Tom|last=Duthie}}</ref> He joined [[Tayport F.C.|Tayport]] on loan in March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/5978/MATI-ZATA-LOANED-TO-TAYPORT-JFC.html|title=Mati Zata loaned to Tayport JFC|date=2 March 2019|website=Dundee United Football Club|access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Dumbarton ===\nZata signed for [[Scottish League One]] club [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] in July 2019, having scored the winner against former club Dundee United whilst playing as a trialist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=4089|title=SONS SIGN FOUR|last=Fullarton|first=Donald|date=11 July 2019|website=Dumbarton Football Club|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He played just ten minutes of league football for the club before joining [[SJFA West Region Premiership]] side [[Rossvale F.C.|Rossvale]] on loan in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=4206|title=PLAYERS GO OUT ON LOAN|last=Galloway|first=Andy|date=22 November 2019|website=Dumbarton Football Club|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> While at Rossvale, he was the target of alleged racial abuse during a match against [[Rutherglen Glencairn F.C.|Rutherglen Glencairn]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gallacher |first1=Liz |title=Racist abuse hurled at teen player with Bishopbriggs junior football team from terraces |url=https://www.kirkintilloch-herald.co.uk/sport/football/racist-abuse-hurled-at-teen-player-with-bishopbriggs-junior-football-team-from-terraces-1-5069941 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |work=Kirkintilloch Herald |date=3 January 2020 }}</ref> Dumbarton's extensive injury problems led to the club recalling Zata from loan in January 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clarke |first1=Fraser |title=Duffy admits he needs to add to his depleted Dumbarton squad |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/duffy-admits-needs-add-depleted-21254397 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |work=Daily Record |date=10 January 2020 |location=Glasgow}}</ref> After making just two more appearances for the club, both in January, Zata was released in March 2020 days after the Scottish football season was suspended due to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Coronavirus crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dumbartonfootballclub.com/news/?mode=view&id=4344|title=Dumbarton Football Club - MATI ZATA LEAVES DFC|website=www.dumbartonfootballclub.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\nZata was born in [[Zimbabwe]] but has dual nationality with [[Scotland|Scottish]] and represented Scotland at under-16 level and Zimbabwe at under-23 level. In 2017, Zata represented Scottish National Team Under-16s in a double header match against Switzerland where he played both matches. In March 2019 Zata was called up to represent Zimbabwe Under-23s in the [[African Cup of Nations]] competition. Zata played both matches against [[Mozambique national football team]] earning 2 caps for Zimbabwe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/5988/INTERNATIONAL-RECOGNITION-FOR-MATI-ZATA.html|title=INTERNATIONAL RECOGNITION FOR MATI ZATA|website=Dundee United Football Club}}</ref>\n\n== Career statistics ==\n\n{{updated|22:51, 18 January 2020 (UTC)}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Club statistics\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Club\n! rowspan=2 | Season\n! colspan=3